## Energy Use and Renewable Energy Adoption

Beyond lifestyle choices, reducing household energy consumption and transitioning to renewable energy sources are vital. Energy use is a significant contributor to global emissions, and improvements in energy efficiency and renewable energy adoption can mitigate climate change effectively.

### Energy Conservation

Simple measures such as turning off lights and unplugging devices when not in use, using energy-efficient appliances and bulbs, and reducing heating and cooling demands can significantly lower household emissions ([Active Sustainability, 2023](https://www.activesustainability.com/climate-change/6-things-you-can-do-to-prevent-climate-change/)).

### Renewable Energy Transition

Shifting from fossil fuel-based energy to renewable sources like solar, wind, hydro, and geothermal is essential for sustainable development and climate mitigation. Renewable energy offers opportunities for energy security, economic development, and health benefits by reducing greenhouse gas emissions and pollutants ([Owusu, Asumadu-Sarkodie, & Dubey, 2016](https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/23311916.2016.1167990)).

However, challenges such as market failures, lack of information, and resource competition must be addressed through policy support, technological innovation, and public awareness to ensure the sustainability of renewable energy deployment.

